##Caryophyllales

#Nyctaginaceae
Bougainvillea: ornamental vine/bush, 3 pink bracts, south America

#Portulacaceae: succulent leaves, colorful flowers
Portulaca [Purslane]

#Caryophyllaceae
Dianthus [Carnation]
Silene [Campion]
Saponaria [Soapwort]

#Droseraceae
Dionaea [Venus flytrap]

#Amaranthaceae
Amaranthus
Spinacia [Spinach]
Beta [Beet]
Chenopodium [Quinoa]
Celosia [Cockscomb]: crested flower head, edible, ornamental

#Cactaceae
Opuntia [Prickly pear]
Cereus
Echinopsis
Schlumbergera [Christmas cactus]
Rhipsalis [Mistletoe cactus]
Ferocactus
Echinocactus
Pachycereus [Cardon]
Carnegiea [Saguaro]
Melocactus [Turk's cap cactus]
Cephalocereus [Old man cactus]
Mammillaria
Pilosocereus [Tree cactus]

#Aizoaceae
Lithops [Living stone]
Mesembryanthemum [Ice plant]



##Ranunculales
=Ranunculaceae: herbs
Pulsatilla [Pasque flower]
Ranunculus [Buttercup]: 5 flashy yellow petals, palmate leaves
Clematis: gardens, numerous large flowers, 4/6/8 petals
Consolida [Larkspur]: gardens, spurred sepal

##Vitales

=Vitaceae
Ampelopsis [Peppervine]
Vitis [Grapevine]

#Saxifragales

=Crassulaceae: succulent herbs
Sedum [Stonecrop]: gardens, small flowers in clusters
Sempervivum [Houseleek]: gardens, flowers on stalks
Crassula [Jade plant]: Africa, houseplant, small flowers in clusters
Kalanchoe: Africa, houseplant, small flowers in clusters
Echeveria: America, houseplant, flowers on stalks

=Grossulariaceae
Ribes [Currant/Gooseberry]: shrub, lobed leaves, thorns, edible berries



#Proteales

=Nelumbonaceae
Nelumbo: lotus, Asia, water gardens
- big flower with many petals
- water-repellent circular leaves
- can generate heat
- seeds can remain dormant long time
=Platanaceae
Platanus: ornamental tree, bark peels off, palmate leaves, achenes aggregated in ball

#Buxales

=Buxaceae: evergreen shrubs
Buxus: small oval leaves, small flowers without petals, hedges

